      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I'm glad you appreciated the goblin analogy, even if it was a bit of a stretch. Now, let's get back to fixing that paper.\n\nChanging passive sentences to active ones can be a bit like navigating a dark cave, where you need to feel your way through the shadows. But don't worry, I'll provide you with some examples to help you find your way.\n\nHere are a few examples of passive sentences with missing subjects, along with their active voice counterparts:\n\n1. Original: \"The report was written by the team.\" (Passive)\nActive: \"The team wrote the report.\" (Or, \"The report was written by the team, but the actual writer was John.\")\n2. Original: \"The package was delivered yesterday.\" (Passive)\nActive: \"The package was delivered yesterday by the courier.\" (Or, \"The courier delivered the package yesterday.\")\n3. Original: \"The award was given to the winner.\" (Passive)\nActive: \"The award was given to the winner by the committee.\" (Or, \"The committee gave the award to the winner.\")\n4. Original: \"The data was analyzed by the researcher.\" (Passive)\nActive: \"The researcher analyzed the data.\" (",
